### Phase 2: Media Uploads & Advanced Settings

---

#### Media Upload Strategy

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The central challenge:** When a teacher uploads an image/audio file and then shares the test, that media must be accessible to students on other devices.

**Recommended approach: Base64 encoding inside the test JSON**

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| **Base64 in JSON** ✅ | No external storage needed; works with existing Drive/Firebase; fully self-contained | Increases JSON size; Firebase RTDB has 10MB per write limit; large media will be slow |
| Firebase Storage | Proper file hosting; URL-based access | Requires enabling Firebase Storage, setting up security rules, uploading SDK; additional Firebase costs |
| External image URLs only | Zero storage needed | Teacher must host images elsewhere; unreliable; poor UX |

**My recommendation:** Start with **Base64** for images (compress/resize to max ~500KB each) and audio (compress with reasonable limits). This keeps everything self-contained within the existing infrastructure. If tests get very large, we can add Firebase Storage later as an upgrade.

**Implementation:**
- File input accepts `image/*` and `audio/*`
- Client-side image resizing (canvas-based, max 800px width) before Base64 encoding
- Audio: accept MP3/WAV up to ~2MB, encode to Base64
- Display previews in the editor and in the student-facing test

