## Limitations & Honest Assessment

Here's my frank assessment of challenges and limitations:

### ✅ Fully feasible (no major obstacles)
- All 7 question types (MC, T/F, matching, fill-blank, unjumble words, unjumble letters, drag-drop)
- Advanced settings per question type
- Student name + course group collection (3A–5D default, teacher-configurable)
- Save/load to localStorage and Google Drive
- Share via code + link
- Beautiful animations for all question types
- Firebase-based real-time response collection
- CSV export of results (including timing and violation data)
- Isolated student page (no access to other tools)
- **Full-screen anti-cheating mode** — Fullscreen API is well-supported in Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Safari
- **Test timing data** — simple timestamp capture, no complexity
- **Course group selection** — dropdown populated from configurable list

### ⚠️ Feasible with caveats
- **Media uploads (images/audio):** Works well with Base64, but there's a practical limit. If a teacher creates a 30-question test with images on every question, the JSON could be 15-20MB — Firebase RTDB limits writes to 16MB. **Mitigation:** Aggressive image compression, and a warning if the test exceeds ~10MB.
- **QR code generation:** Requires adding a small library (e.g., `qrcode.js`, ~33KB). This is a minor addition but worth noting since the project currently has no npm dependencies.
- **Drag & drop on mobile:** HTML5 drag-and-drop has poor mobile support. **Mitigation:** Use touch event handling (touchstart/touchmove/touchend) along with mouse events, which I'll implement manually (no library needed).

### ⚠️ Requires setup outside this codebase
- **Google Sheets integration:** The teacher needs to create a Google Apps Script web app and paste the webhook URL. I can provide detailed instructions and even a pre-built Apps Script they can copy-paste, but this is a one-time setup step that can't be fully automated from our side.
- **Firebase security rules:** The current RTDB rules may need updating to allow public read of `tests/{code}` for unauthenticated students. I'll provide the exact rules to add.
- **Hosting:** For the shareable link to work as a URL (not just a code), the platform needs to be hosted somewhere publicly accessible (e.g., Firebase Hosting, GitHub Pages, school server).

### ❌ Not realistic within this project's architecture
- **Audio recording in browser** (e.g., teacher recording a prompt): Technically possible with the MediaRecorder API, but adds significant complexity and file size. **Recommendation:** Keep it to file upload only for audio.
- **Real-time collaborative test editing** (multiple teachers editing the same test): Would require a fundamentally different architecture. Out of scope.
- **Automatic grading of free-text responses:** Fill-in-the-blank can check exact matches (with case-insensitivity toggle), but natural language understanding is beyond scope.

